	doi = {10.1051/0004-6361/202346173},
	abstract = {Measurements of the growth rate of structures at z {\textless} 0.1 with peculiar velocity surveys have the potential of testing the validity of general relativity on cosmic scales. In this work, we present growth-rate measurements from realistic simulated sets of type-Ia supernovae (SNe Ia) from the Zwicky Transient Facility (ZTF). We describe our simulation methodology, the light-curve ﬁtting, and peculiar velocity estimation. Using the maximum likelihood method, we derived constraints on f σ8 using only ZTF SN Ia peculiar velocities. We carefully tested the method and we quantiﬁed biases due to selection eﬀects (photometric detection, spectroscopic follow-up for typing) on several independent realizations. We simulated the equivalent of 6 years of ZTF data, and considering an unbiased spectroscopically typed sample at z {\textless} 0.06, we obtained unbiased estimates of f σ8 with an average uncertainty of 19\% precision. We also investigated the information gain in applying bias correction methods. Our results validate our framework, which can be used on real ZTF data.},
